# Consultation & Treatment Plan Module Review

The **Comprehensive Consultation and Session Module** is now fully integrated into your Flutter App!

## What was built:

1. **Intensive Consultation Form (`Phase 20`)**
   - Built a comprehensive scrollable form in [ConsultationScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/consultations/screens/consultation_screen.dart#16-35).
   - Captures detailed conversational information: Chief Complaint, Medical History, Surgeries, Medications, Allergies, Chronic Diseases.
   - Captures lifestyle habits: Diet, Sleep, Exercise, Addictions, Stress.
   - Includes Vitals (BP, Pulse) and digital consent tracking for physical contact therapies.
   - Captures the exact Consultation Fee optionally.

2. **Smart Session Auto-Scheduler Engine**
   - Automatically kicks in right after a Consultation is saved.
   - The doctor selects the **Treatment Type** (which auto-populates the base fee from their settings), the **Number of Sessions**, the **Interval (in Days) between sessions**, and a **Preferred Time**.
   - **Smart Overlap Handling**: The algorithm fetches the clinic's maximum physical `bed_count`. If 3 beds are available and 3 patients are already booked for 10:00 AM on a generated interval date, the scheduler will intelligently shift this new patient's session to 10:30 AM to ensure physical beds are never double-booked.

3. **Session Interactivity & Management**
   - Treatment plans display a progress bar (e.g., 2/5 sessions completed).
   - Tapping an upcoming session opens the **Record Session** screen.
   - Doctors can input session-specific vitals, session notes (reactions, improvements), and use the Native Camera/Gallery to upload **compressed** photos for medical records efficiently!

4. **Integrated Patient Timeline**
   - The [PatientProfileScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/patients/screens/patient_profile_screen.dart#11-19) displays a massive unified chronological history fetching **Appointments**, **Consultations**, and **Treatment Sessions** all in a single elegant timeline UI.
   - Features a permanent floating "Consult" button to rapidly trigger state changes.

## Verification Steps
Please run your Flutter app and perform the following end-to-end test:
1. Go to the **Patients Tab** and select an existing patient.
2. Tap the **Consult** Floating Action Button.
3. Fill out the massive Consultation form we just created.
4. Hit **Submit** — Accept the prompt to immediately auto-schedule a Treatment Plan.
5. In the Treatment Plan screen, choose a Treatment, enter total sessions (e.g., `5`), interval days (e.g., `2`), and check the generated Sessions list!
6. Tap a generated Session to record vitals and upload a photo!

Everything should work flawlessly and elegantly since all 13 fields are now mapped to PocketBase!

## Bug Fixes Applied
- **Relation Field Type Fix**: Addressed an issue where [patient](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/scripts/setup_pocketbase.dart#132-148) and [doctor](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/scripts/setup_pocketbase.dart#112-131) relation fields were either accidentally deleted or pointing to the wrong base collections in PocketBase. The flutter app's navigation endpoints ([PatientProfileScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/patients/screens/patient_profile_screen.dart#11-19), `AppRouter`, etc.) were updated to explicitly retrieve and pass the associated `doctorId` mapped directly to the patient, instead of relying on the currently authenticated user session (which could erroneously be a Clinic ID).
- **Graceful Timestamp Parsing**: Mitigated a catastrophic `Bad state: Invalid or unknown type value` crash caused by PocketBase v0.23 omitting default timestamp fields across newly created records. `ConsultationModel.dart` was updated to securely extract `created`, `updated`, and nested `expand` payloads using safer getter methods instead of rigid generic typecasting.

## Phase 21: Architecure Hierarchy Overhaul

This phase shifted the flat data model to a properly nested **Consultation Hierarchy**:

1. **Expanded Patient Demographics**
   - The [PatientModel](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/patients/models/patient_model.dart#3-87) now explicitly captures `Age`, `Gender`, `Occupation`, and `Email` directly into the database schema rather than inside generic note sections.
   - The **Walk-In Appointment** tab aggressively collects these new metrics natively without needing a secondary "registration" step.

2. **Hierarchical Profile Viewing**
   - The [PatientProfileScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/patients/screens/patient_profile_screen.dart#11-19) has been physically split into 3 distinct tabs: 
     - **Basic Details** (Displaying the new expanded demographics)
     - **History** (The classic Appointments timeline)
     - **Treatments** (A targeted, reverse-chronological list of unique Consultations).
   
3. **Read-Only Consultation Mode**
   - Tapping an existing Consultation from the new Treatments tab routes directly back to [ConsultationScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/consultations/screens/consultation_screen.dart#16-35), but intelligently locks it into `View Mode`.
   - `View Mode` gracefully restricts all text inputs while dynamically appending an embedded **Treatment Plan Sessions** sub-view anchored at the bottom of the scroll.
   - If a Consultation somehow lacks an active plan, a centralized `Create Treatment Plan` trigger is exposed right there within the view! Or, it renders interactive `RecordSessionScreen` buttons if sessions exist.

## Phase 22: Appointment & Navigation Refinements

Based on user feedback, several critical UX adjustments have been incorporated into the appointment booking and consultation modules:

1. **Treatments Navigation Fix**
   - Corrected an issue where clicking an ongoing Consultation inside the `PatientProfileScreen > Treatments` tab was crashing due to stricter dynamic argument constraints within `AppRouter`. The UI now flawlessly re-opens the Consultation details in uneditable view mode.
   
2. **Call-By Calendar Embed**
   - Eliminated the friction of endlessly swiping weeks into the future on the [AvailableSlots](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/core/services/scheduling_service.dart#67-96) screen for Call-By appointments.
   - Designed a new sleek inline **Appointment Date picker** built directly into the [CreateAppointmentScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/appointments/screens/create_appointment_screen.dart#15-24)'s main layout that defaults when `Call-By` is activated.
   
3. **Walk-In Overrides & Blackouts**
   - Enhanced the [SchedulingService](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/core/services/scheduling_service.dart#21-285) internal algorithms to constantly check against the live exact device time (`DateTime.now()`).
   - More crucially, when utilizing **Walk-In** bookings, strict constraints are lifted. Staff can now forcefully select ANY slot (even if past or booked), explicitly saving the Walk-In interval securely into the pocketbase database synced precisely to the exact submitted machine time.

## Phase 31: Advanced Scheduling & History Workflows

This phase fundamentally upgraded the logic bridging Consultations, Calendaring, and Patient Histories:

1. **Doctor Scheduling Constraints**
   - The [CreateTreatmentPlanScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/treatments/screens/create_treatment_plan_screen.dart#13-30) date picker is now definitively locked. Using `selectableDayPredicate`, it physically disables clicking on days that do not fall within the doctor's explicitly configured `workingDays` (e.g., if a doctor doesn't work Sundays, Sunday is disabled on the calendar!).

2. **PocketBase Session Syncing Fix**
   - We corrected a data fragmentation bug! Auto-created sessions now explicitly pass their `consultationId` relation back to PocketBase when generating, ensuring the "Active Treatment Plan" card inside [ConsultationScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/consultations/screens/consultation_screen.dart#16-35) populates instantly.

3. **Treatment Session Calendar Badges**
   - We heavily upgraded the generic Appointment structure. When Treatment Sessions are auto-generated, they now physically block out the doctor's calendar using the newly created [session](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/scripts/setup_pocketbase.dart#196-214) appointment type. 
   - These dynamically render inside [AppointmentListScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/appointments/screens/appointment_list_screen.dart#11-18) with a deeply shaded primary-color card containing a custom healing icon labeled specifically as **"Treatment Session"** so they don't blend in with standard Call-By or Walk-In patients!

4. **Accurate Check-in/Check-out History Tracking**
   - We've completely rebuilt the [PatientProfileScreen](file:///c:/App%20Development/PMS/lib/features/patients/screens/patient_profile_screen.dart#11-19) **History Tab** logic to drop "ghost" appointments.
   - Now, if an appointment is just sitting on the calendar (`Scheduled` status), it will intentionally NOT pollute the patient's history timeline.
   - It only appears on the timeline the moment the patient physically arrives and the "Common Form" is submitted (capturing their exact `checkInTime`!).
   - Once the doctor taps "Done" on the appointment later (capturing `checkOutTime`), the History timeline elegantly updates to display precise explicit timestamps: e.g., `Check-in (Form Filled): 10:15 AM` and `Check-out (Done): 11:00 AM`.
